### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

Most components are setting `styles` or `styleUrls` to an array with a single value.

```ts
@Component({
  style: `:host { ... }`
})
class MyCmp {
}
```

P.S.: I hope that this isn't a duplicate. It feels like something that was discussed multiple times but I couldn't find the issue.
Sorry if I missed it.

### Proposed solution

It would be a nice syntactic sugar to allow `style` & `styleUrl` shortcuts.

I'd be happy to help with a PR.

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

compiler-cli, compiler

### Description

## Transformer in the way

Injectables' dependencies are currently guessed by analyzing the constructor parameter types.
This typing information is lost after transforming TypeScript to ECMAScript. In order to fix this, the compiler has to run a transformer that converts this information into something like:
```ts
MyCmp.ctorParameters = () => [
   { type: MyService }
];
```
Cf. https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/3a60063a54d850c50ce962a8a39ce01cfee71398/packages/compiler-cli/src/transformers/downlevel_decorators_transform/downlevel_decorators_transform.ts

The problem with this approach is that it slows down community initiatives of integrating Angular with other tools. e.g. Vite, Vitest, SWC...
This forces tools to hack their way through. For instance, jest-preset-angular downloads the internal CLI transformer: https://github.com/thymikee/jest-preset-angular/blob/f24156ea1f7532c02c44d8d023b54623a4bccccd/scripts/prebuild.js#L9

## `inject()` to the rescue

The good news is that an app using only `inject()` instead of constructor param types to retrieve dependencies will not need this transformer:
```ts
class MyCmp {
 myService = inject(MyService);
}
```

The problem with using `inject()` function this way is that it doesn't allow injecting dependencies manually. This means that all tests will need the `TestBed` or similar to control dependencies resolution.
To allow manual instantiation, the current alternative would be something **non-explicit, verbose and error-prone** like this:

```ts
class MyCmp {
   // let's not do this
  constructor(myService?: MyService) {
    this.myService = myService ?? inject(MyService);
  }
}
```

### Proposed solution

Compiler should bypass type-based dependency injection when a default value is set and the given type can't be resolved.
This would allow the following syntax which currently works if this transformer is disabled:

```ts
class MyCmp {
  constructor(private myService = inject(MyService)) {}
}
```

This has the following advantages:
- âœ¨ constructor parameters transformer is not needed anymore... so easier integration with existing tools
- âœ¨ manual instantiation is still possible
- âœ¨ all the benefits of `inject`: type-inference, consistent way of injecting class-based & injection-token based deps: `locale = inject(LOCALE_ID)`, controlling options (e.g. optional, self) through flags instead of decorators.

### Alternatives considered

Use `inject()` and never instantiate manually.

As of Angular v15, the deprecated `relativeLinkResolution` config option of the Router is removed.  This migration cleans up (removes) the `relativeLinkResolution` fields from the Router config objects in applications code.

```ts
import { RouterModule } from '@angular/router';

RouterModule.forRoot([], {
  relativeLinkResolution: 'legacy',
  enableTracing: false,
});
```

```ts
import { RouterModule } from '@angular/router';

RouterModule.forRoot([], {
  // the `relativeLinkResolution` is removed
  enableTracing: false,
});
```

